// parse_int2.su — parse a 1-or-2 digit non-negative integer from a string,
// ON THE SUBSTRATE. The first verified piece of calc step-d
// (parse-on-substrate; planning/23): the host does I/O only, while digit
// extraction and place-value run on the Sutra substrate — no host parsing.
//
// Mechanism (every step a substrate op, measured 2026-05-24):
//   - string_char_at(s, i) returns the CODEPOINT as a real number on the
//     substrate ('5' -> 53.0; out-of-bounds index -> 0.0, saturated).
//   - digit value = codepoint - 48  ('5' -> 5).
//   - length-aware place value WITHOUT any comparison, using n = string_length:
//       value = (c0-48)*(1 + 9*(n-1)) + (c1-48)*(n-1)
//       n=1: (c0-48)*1 + (c1-48)*0   = c0-48   (the c1 term is killed by *0,
//                                                so the out-of-bounds 0 codepoint
//                                                cannot contaminate the result)
//       n=2: (c0-48)*10 + (c1-48)*1
//   - make_real lifts the final scalar onto the real axis so the host can
//     decode it with real() (a 0-d codepoint scalar does NOT lift through bare
//     arithmetic — that was the blocker; make_real is the fix). switch.su uses
//     the equivalent real_number(x) constructor.
//
// SCOPE — 1 to 2 digits ("2-digit cap to start", planning/23). A 3+-digit
// input silently truncates to its first two digits, so the caller must ensure
// <= 2 digits until the variable-length generalization lands (a Sutra
// accumulator loop / digit array). NOT yet wired into calc.py — this is the
// verified building block that unblocks the full substrate parser.
function vector parse_int2(string s) {
    scalar n  = s.string_length();
    scalar c0 = s.string_char_at(0) - 48.0;
    scalar c1 = s.string_char_at(1) - 48.0;
    return make_real(c0 * (1.0 + 9.0 * (n - 1.0)) + c1 * (n - 1.0));
}

function vector main() { return parse_int2("42"); }
